Part 1: DNS — What You Actually Need to Know

Your intuition was mostly right. Let me sharpen it.

The flow you described is correct but incomplete. When a device joins a network: DHCP assigns an IP, a default gateway, and a DNS server address. From that point forward, every time that device wants to reach anything by name (google.com, internal-app.corp, malware-c2.ru), it sends a DNS query to that DNS server. The DNS server resolves it and returns an IP. The device then connects to that IP.

Why DNS is a goldmine for security:

DNS is one of the very few protocols that almost everything talks to. Malware talks to DNS. Exfiltration tools use DNS. Ransomware beacons over DNS. A compromised host that can't reach the internet directly will still often try DNS because port 53 is almost always allowed outbound. This makes DNS logs uniquely valuable — they are a near-universal record of "what was every device trying to reach."

The types of DNS logs that exist:
Log Type	What It Is	Security Value
DNS Query logs	Client asked for a name, resolver received it	HIGH — this is what people mean 99% of the time
DNS Response logs	What the resolver answered back (IP returned, NXDOMAIN, etc.)	HIGH — tells you if resolution succeeded and to what IP
DNS Zone transfer logs	Replication between DNS servers	Medium — attack vector if exposed
DNS server audit logs	Config changes to the DNS service itself	Medium — detects tampering
DNSSEC validation logs	Cryptographic validation failures	Lower for most orgs

When a client says "DNS logs," they mean query + response logs. That is the data. Everything else is secondary.

The critical insight about DNS coverage — you nailed this:

You are absolutely right that the question is not just "do we have DNS logs" but "which devices' DNS traffic do we actually see?" If a device is using a DNS server that isn't logging, it's invisible to you. This is one of the most important questions you need to ask tomorrow.
Part 2: The Engineering Mental Model for Any New Data Source

Here is the framework you asked for. Burn this into your head. Every single time a new data source comes up, walk through these five layers in order.

Layer 1: What is the source and what does it actually log?

    What system/service generates this data?
    What events does it record? What does it not record?
    What is the log format? (Structured JSON, syslog, CEF, custom?)
    What is the log volume and retention at the source?

Layer 2: How does the data get to Sentinel?

    Is there a native connector? An agent? A Diagnostic Setting? A custom data collection rule (DCR)?
    Is it push or pull?
    Who configured it? Who owns the pipeline?
    Is there potential for data loss in transit?

Layer 3: What table does it land in, and is it normalized?

    Raw table (like AzureDiagnostics) vs. purpose-built table (like DNSQueryLogs)
    Is it in ASIM format or does it need a parser?
    What fields are actually populated vs. theoretically available?
    Is the _Im_Dns() function returning data, and does it look right?

Layer 4: What is the coverage and completeness?

    Which assets/devices/segments are actually covered by this log source?
    What falls outside coverage?
    Are there gaps you need to document?
    Is the data complete enough to be reliable for detections?

Layer 5: What can you detect with it, and who owns detection engineering?

    What threat scenarios does this data enable you to detect?
    What is the noise level / false positive risk?
    Who is responsible for writing and maintaining rules?
    Are there existing community or vendor rules you can leverage (OOTB Sentinel analytics, GitHub community, MITRE mappings)?

This is your checklist for every client conversation about a new data source. If you can't answer all five layers, you are not ready to say the data source is "working."
Part 3: The Detection Engineering Boundary Problem

You mentioned your team doesn't manage detections. This needs to be crystal clear in writing with every client. Here's how to think about it:

There are three distinct roles in this space and clients often conflate them:

    Log ingestion engineering — Getting data into Sentinel reliably. This is plumbing. You own this.
    Detection engineering — Writing, tuning, and maintaining analytics rules. This requires ongoing security expertise. If you don't own this, say so explicitly.
    SOC / Alert response — Acting on the detections that fire. This is usually a different team or an MSSP.

The client's ticket assumes all three happen automatically when logs arrive. They don't. This needs to be a standing part of your client onboarding and intake process.
Part 4: What's Actually Happening in This Sentinel Environment

Based on what you described, here is my read of the situation:

The _Im_Dns() function returning data is the most important signal you found. That function is the ASIM DNS parser — it normalizes DNS data from whatever underlying source exists into a standard schema. The fact that it returns data means DNS logs are flowing somewhere. The question is where they come from.

Your observation about AzureDiagnostics showing Azure Firewall DNS proxy logs is likely the answer. Azure Firewall has a DNS proxy feature — when enabled, it intercepts DNS queries from VNet resources, resolves them, and can log those queries. That is a legitimate and common architecture. What it means from a coverage standpoint is that only resources routing their DNS through that Azure Firewall are represented in the logs.

The DNSQueryLogs table is a separate, newer table that Azure Private DNS Resolver uses. If they're using Private DNS Resolver, logs land there. If they're using Azure Firewall DNS proxy, logs land in AzureDiagnostics. These are different architectures and it matters which one you're looking at.

