Yes, you are exactly right. Let me confirm each piece so you can build on it with confidence.

ASIM is a normalization standard. It defines a schema — meaning a specific set of field names, data types, and expected values — so that the same kind of event always looks the same regardless of where it came from. A DNS query from an Azure Firewall and a DNS query from an Infoblox appliance are completely different raw log formats, but after ASIM normalization they both have DnsQuery, SrcIpAddr, DnsResponseCode, and so on in the same fields.

The payoff you identified is correct. Because the schema is consistent, a detection rule written against ASIM fields works against any source that has been normalized to that schema. You write it once, it covers everything.

Your understanding of _Im_Dns() is accurate. That function is called a unifying parser. When you run it, it is executing KQL under the hood that queries multiple underlying tables it knows might contain DNS data, runs source-specific filtering parsers against each one to normalize the raw fields into the ASIM schema, unions all those results together, and returns them to you as a single clean dataset. You never have to know which table the data came from or what the raw field names were.

The "query time" piece you mentioned is important. The data is not transformed when it lands. It arrives raw and sits raw in the table. The parsing happens at the moment you run the query. This is called query-time normalization and it means the original data is always preserved underneath.

So yes — keep going. You are building this correctly.

