How Do You Know If You're Looking at the Right Logs?

This is a really important question and the answer has a name: DNS resolver logs or more specifically recursive resolver query logs. When security people say "give me DNS logs" this is what they mean 99% of the time.

Here is how you identify them when you're looking at a table:

You are looking at the right logs if you see:

    A source IP address — the client device that made the query
    A queried domain name — what they asked for
    A query type — A record, AAAA, MX, TXT, etc.
    A response code — NOERROR means it resolved, NXDOMAIN means the domain doesn't exist, REFUSED means the resolver blocked it
    A timestamp

In ASIM those fields are SrcIpAddr, DnsQuery, DnsQueryType, DnsResponseCode, and TimeGenerated.

You are NOT looking at the right logs if you only see:

    Configuration changes to DNS settings
    Zone transfer events
    DNS server service start/stop events

Those are DNS server audit logs, not query logs. Useful for different purposes but not what you want for security monitoring.

The quick sanity check query:
kusto

_Im_Dns()
| project TimeGenerated, SrcIpAddr, DnsQuery, DnsQueryType, DnsResponseCode, EventResult
| take 20

If SrcIpAddr is populated with real client IPs and DnsQuery contains real domain names, you are looking at resolver query logs. If those fields are empty or the data looks like administrative events, something is wrong with either the source or the parser mapping.

