What is a DNS Proxy in This Context?

Normally when a device wants to resolve a domain name it sends a DNS query directly to whatever DNS server it has been configured to use. The device and the DNS server talk directly to each other.

A DNS proxy sits in the middle of that conversation. The device sends its query to the proxy instead of directly to the DNS server. The proxy receives the query, forwards it to the real DNS server on the device's behalf, gets the answer back, and returns it to the device. From the device's perspective nothing feels different. But now the proxy has seen every single query and can log it.

Think of it like a postal worker who intercepts every letter you send, writes down who you sent it to and when, then drops it in the mailbox for you. You don't notice anything different. But now there's a record of everything you tried to send.

In Azure, when you enable DNS proxy on the Azure Firewall, your VNet resources (virtual machines, services, anything running in your Azure cloud network) are configured to send their DNS queries to the firewall instead of directly to Azure's default DNS. The firewall logs every query and response, then forwards the request on to the actual resolver.
What is Azure Private DNS Resolver?

Azure Private DNS Resolver is a dedicated Microsoft-managed service whose entire job is to handle DNS resolution for your Azure environment. It is not a firewall. It does not filter traffic or protect anything. It purely resolves names and can log what it resolves.

Why would a company use this instead of or alongside Azure Firewall DNS proxy?

Imagine a large enterprise with dozens of Azure environments, multiple regions, and a connection back to their on-premises office network. They have internal domain names that only exist inside the company — things like payroll.internal.corp or db-server-01.eastus.internal. These names don't exist on the public internet. They only resolve inside the company's network.

The problem is that DNS resolution needs to work seamlessly whether a request is coming from an Azure VM, a laptop in the office, or a developer working from home over VPN. Getting all of those different environments to resolve internal names consistently is genuinely complicated.

Private DNS Resolver solves this by acting as a central DNS hub that knows how to handle both internal company names and public internet names, and can forward queries between on-premises DNS servers and Azure DNS in a controlled way.

The security logging benefit is that because everything flows through the resolver, you get a complete picture of DNS queries across your Azure environment in one place.

Simple analogy: Azure Firewall DNS proxy is like a security guard at the door who also happens to write down everyone who comes and goes. Private DNS Resolver is like a dedicated receptionist whose entire job is managing who goes where in the building and keeping the visitor log. Two different jobs. One happens to produce a visitor log as a side effect. The other was built specifically to manage traffic and the log is a deliberate feature.
Are All Devices Covered? VMs, Laptops, Computers?

This is the most important coverage question and the answer is: it depends entirely on how the environment is architected, and you cannot assume everything is covered.

Here is the reality of what a typical enterprise environment looks like and what gets captured:

Azure VMs and cloud workloads — If the VNet (the private cloud network those VMs live in) is configured to use either the Azure Firewall DNS proxy or Private DNS Resolver as its DNS server, those VMs are covered. If the VNet is using Azure's default DNS directly, they are not covered.

On-premises computers and servers — These are physical or virtual machines sitting in a company's own data center or office. They almost certainly have their own DNS infrastructure, typically Windows Server DNS. Their queries never touch Azure Firewall or Private DNS Resolver unless the company has explicitly set up DNS forwarding from on-premises to Azure. Most companies have not done this. This is a major gap.

Laptops and remote workers — These depend on how VPN is configured. If a remote worker connects via VPN and that VPN routes DNS through the corporate DNS server, those queries may or may not make it to Azure logging depending on what that corporate DNS server does with them. If the laptop is using the DNS server assigned by the local coffee shop Wi-Fi, those queries are completely invisible to the company.

The bottom line is that no single DNS logging method captures everything by default. Coverage is a deliberate architectural choice and most environments have gaps they don't know about.
