The DNS AMA connector (AMA stands for Azure Monitor Agent) is specifically for collecting logs from Windows Server DNS. You install the agent on the Windows servers that are acting as DNS servers in the environment, and those logs flow into Sentinel.

You would suggest this when:

    The client has on-premises Windows DNS servers handling queries for physical machines, office laptops, or servers in their data center
    Azure Firewall or Private DNS Resolver only covers the cloud portion and you have identified an on-prem gap
    The client has domain-joined machines and Active Directory, which almost always means Windows DNS is in play somewhere
    The client specifically needs to see DNS queries from endpoints that never touch Azure infrastructure

You would not suggest this when:

    The environment is fully cloud-native with no on-premises Windows DNS
    The client has a third-party DNS solution already
    The operational overhead of deploying and maintaining agents across DNS servers is not feasible

