What Does a Normal Enterprise DNS Environment Actually Look Like?

Here is a realistic picture of what you will encounter most often:

A mid-to-large enterprise typically has Windows Active Directory on-premises. Active Directory depends heavily on DNS — it uses DNS to locate domain controllers, authenticate users, and route internal traffic. This means there are almost always Windows DNS servers on-premises that have been running for years, sometimes decades, handling queries for every domain-joined machine in the building.

When that company moves workloads to Azure, they set up VNets and Azure resources. Early on they often just use Azure's default DNS for cloud resources because it's easy. Over time they realize their cloud resources need to resolve internal names, so they start configuring DNS more deliberately. This is usually where Azure Firewall DNS proxy or Private DNS Resolver enters the picture.

The result is that most enterprises you encounter will have at least two DNS environments — one on-prem (Windows DNS) and one in Azure — and they may or may not be forwarding between them. The DNS logging in Sentinel may only be capturing one of those two environments. The client may not even realize this.

Your job as the engineer is to ask the question and draw the map. During the meeting tomorrow, a simple whiteboard question like "walk me through where your DNS servers are and what devices point to each one" will reveal the full picture faster than any technical investigation.
The Decision Framework for Recommending a DNS Logging Approach

When a client says they want DNS logs, here is the thinking process to walk through:

First — map the environment. Where are the DNS servers? Cloud only, on-prem only, or hybrid? What devices point to what DNS servers?

Second — identify what they actually want to monitor. Cloud workloads only? On-prem endpoints? Everything? The answer determines which methods you need.

Third — check what infrastructure already exists. Do they have Azure Firewall already? Then DNS proxy is low friction. Do they have Windows DNS on-prem? Then AMA is the path. Are they starting fresh? Then Private DNS Resolver is worth considering.

Fourth — think about coverage gaps explicitly. Document what is covered and what is not. Never let a client assume they have complete coverage when they don't. This protects you and helps them make informed decisions.

