Great question and this is genuinely important to understand before writing detections or validating anything.
The Three Levels of ASIM DNS Functions

There are three tiers and they serve different purposes.

Tier 1 — The Unifying Parser: _Im_Dns()

This is the one you have been using. It calls every source-specific parser underneath it, unions all the results, and returns everything in one normalized dataset. The Im stands for intermediary — it is the middle layer that brings everything together.

Use this when you want a complete picture across all DNS sources in the environment. Most OOTB detections in Sentinel are written against this function precisely because it covers everything regardless of what the underlying source is.

Tier 2 — The Filtering Parsers: _ASim_Dns_[SourceName]()

These are source-specific. Each one targets exactly one data source. Examples:

    _ASim_Dns_AzureFirewall() — only Azure Firewall DNS proxy logs
    _ASim_Dns_MicrosoftNXlog() — only Windows DNS via NXLog agent
    _ASim_Dns_InfobloxBloxOne() — only Infoblox

The ASim prefix means Advanced Security Information Model — these are the individual building blocks that _Im_Dns() calls internally.

Tier 3 — The Raw Tables

Not functions at all — just the underlying tables like AzureDiagnostics, DNSQueryLogs, DnsEvents. Raw, unparsed, source-specific. You go here when you need to see exactly what landed, verify parser mappings, or troubleshoot.
Should Detections Use _Im_Dns() or the Individual Parsers?

The answer depends on what the detection is trying to do and this is an important engineering decision.

Use _Im_Dns() for detections when:

You want the detection to work regardless of what DNS source the environment uses. This is the whole point of ASIM. If a client swaps from Azure Firewall DNS proxy to Private DNS Resolver six months from now, a detection written against _Im_Dns() keeps working without any changes. You write it once, it covers everything. This is the right default for most detections.

Use the individual _ASim_Dns_[Source]() parser when:

    You need to detect something that only exists in one specific source — a field that Azure Firewall logs but no other source does
    You are troubleshooting whether a detection is firing correctly and want to isolate one source to eliminate variables
    Performance matters — querying one source-specific parser is faster than querying the unifying parser across all sources, which matters at scale in large environments
    You know with certainty the environment only has one DNS source and want the query to be explicit and lean

The practical reality for your work:

For OOTB Sentinel analytics rules, Microsoft writes them against _Im_Dns(). Those rules work as long as the ASIM parser is correctly mapping the data. Your job as the engineer validating a new DNS source is to confirm that _Im_Dns() is returning good normalized data — because if it is, all those OOTB rules automatically have coverage.

If the parser is broken or a field is not mapping correctly, the OOTB rule will either not fire or produce garbage results. That is why your data quality check in Step 5 matters so much — you are essentially validating that the ASIM layer is working correctly so detections can trust it.
The Functions You Should Know By Name
Function	What It Is	When to Use It
_Im_Dns()	Unifying parser — all sources, normalized	Default for detections and investigation
_Im_Dns(starttime=, endtime=)	Same but with time parameters for performance	When running against large time ranges
_ASim_Dns_AzureFirewall()	Azure Firewall DNS proxy only	Troubleshooting, source isolation, Azure-only environments
_ASim_Dns_MicrosoftNXlog()	Windows DNS via NXLog	On-prem Windows DNS troubleshooting
_ASim_Dns_Native()	Microsoft's native DNS table (DNSQueryLogs)	Private DNS Resolver environments
imDns()	Older version of the unifying parser — no underscore prefix	Legacy — you may see this in older rules, prefer _Im_Dns()

The difference between imDns() and _Im_Dns() is worth knowing. The underscore prefix version is the newer built-in workspace function that Microsoft deploys automatically. The non-underscore version is the older community-deployed parser that had to be manually installed. If you see both in a workspace it usually means the workspace has been around for a while and the old parser was never cleaned up. Always prefer the underscore version.
One More Thing Worth Knowing — Parameters

_Im_Dns() accepts parameters that let you filter before the union happens, which is much more efficient than filtering after. The most useful ones:
kusto

// Only return failed queries — NXDOMAIN, REFUSED etc.
_Im_Dns(eventresult='Failure')

// Only return queries for a specific domain
_Im_Dns(domain_has_any=dynamic(['suspicious-domain.com']))

// Limit the time window at the parser level for performance
_Im_Dns(starttime=ago(1h), endtime=now())

Filtering inside the function call is faster than piping and then filtering because the filtering happens before the union across all sources rather than after. In a production detection rule this difference matters.

