This is a really important thing to lock in your head because the naming trips people up constantly.
Why It Is _ASim_Dns_AzureFirewall and Not _ASim_Dns_AzureDiagnostics

AzureDiagnostics is just a container table. It is a generic bucket that Microsoft uses to collect diagnostic logs from dozens of completely different Azure services — firewalls, key vaults, SQL databases, load balancers, and more. It has no identity of its own. It is just where stuff lands.

Azure Firewall is the actual product that generated the DNS log.

So when Microsoft named the parser they named it after the product that created the data, not the table it happened to land in. The parser is _ASim_Dns_AzureFirewall() because the log came from an Azure Firewall. The fact that it landed in AzureDiagnostics is just a storage detail — a plumbing concern. The parser handles that internally. It knows to look inside AzureDiagnostics and filter for Category == "AzureFirewallDnsProxy" so you never have to think about it.
The Mental Model to Carry Forward

Always think in terms of product not table.

When you are looking for a parser name, ask yourself:

    What product or service generated this log?

Not:

    What table did it land in?

The parser name will almost always follow the product name. A few examples to make this stick:
Product That Generated the Log	Table It Lands In	Parser Name
Azure Firewall	AzureDiagnostics	_ASim_Dns_AzureFirewall()
Azure Private DNS Resolver	DNSQueryLogs	_ASim_Dns_Native()
Windows DNS Server	DnsEvents	_ASim_Dns_MicrosoftNXlog() or _ASim_Dns_MicrosoftOMS()
Infoblox BloxOne	CommonSecurityLog	_ASim_Dns_InfobloxBloxOne()

