How to Identify a Container Table

There is no single official label Microsoft applies that says "this is a container table." But there are clear signals you learn to recognize.

Signal 1 — A Category or Type column exists at the top level

Container tables almost always have a field whose entire job is to tell you what kind of log this row contains. In AzureDiagnostics that field is Category. In CommonSecurityLog it is DeviceVendor and DeviceProduct. In Event it is EventLog and EventID. If you look at a table and the first thing you need to do to make sense of it is filter by some category or type field, it is almost certainly a container.

Signal 2 — The table name is generic

Tables named after a specific product are almost never containers. Tables with broad, generic names almost always are. Compare:

    SigninLogs — specific, one source, Azure AD sign-ins only
    AzureDiagnostics — generic, massive container
    SecurityEvent — generic, Windows security events from many machines
    CommonSecurityLog — generic, CEF format logs from hundreds of vendors

Signal 3 — Columns are inconsistently populated

Container tables often have dozens of columns but any given row only has a handful populated. This is because different sources use different fields and the table has to accommodate all of them. If you look at a table and see that most rows have large numbers of empty columns, you are looking at a container.

