Really good engineering question and the answer has important implications for how you document environments.
Can the Fields and Categories in AzureDiagnostics Change?

Yes — and this is one of the most important things to understand about container tables.

AzureDiagnostics is dynamically schematized. This means the columns in the table are not fixed. When a new Azure service starts writing to it that uses a field no previous service has ever used, Azure Monitor adds that column to the table automatically. The table literally grows new columns as new sources onboard.

The practical implications of this are significant:

What you see is only what has been sent. If you run a summary of categories and see 10, those are the 10 services that have actually sent logs to that workspace. There could be 50 more categories that this table is capable of collecting that simply have no data in this environment yet. Your 10 categories tell you what is active, not what is possible.

Fields can be empty for entire categories. A column might exist in the table because one service uses it, but every row from a different service will have that column blank. This is why AzureDiagnostics looks so sparse when you browse it.

The schema you see today could be different tomorrow. If the client enables a new Azure service that logs to AzureDiagnostics, new categories and potentially new columns appear automatically with no action required on your part.
